<h2>PfISD Career Academies already connect to ACC</h2>
<p>Pflugerville ISD operates Career Academies with ACC in accounting, automotive, construction technology (with electrical and plumbing apprenticeships), advanced manufacturing, and culinary arts. PfISD also has a P-TECH academy and an Early College High School program. CTE programs serve over 8,000 PfISD students. Source: <a href="https://www.pfisd.net/programs/career-and-technical-education/ms-courses-and-hs-programs" target="_blank">PfISD CTE</a>.</p>
<p>In-district status removes the cost barrier for students who want to continue at ACC after graduation. It also strengthens dual credit affordability and credential stacking. With PfISD's new CTE center opening in 2027 and the Downtown East development creating potential space for local ACC classes, the physical infrastructure is coming. In-district status makes it affordable to use.</p>

<h2>Wage outcomes</h2>
<p>Bureau of Labor Statistics data (2024) shows that workers with some college or an associate degree earn a median of $1,099 per week ($57,148/year), compared to $930/week ($48,360/year) for high school diploma holders. That is an $8,788 annual premium. Over a 30-year career, it adds up to approximately $264,000 in additional earnings. Source: <a href="https://www.bls.gov/careeroutlook/2025/data-on-display/education-pays.htm" target="_blank">BLS Education Pays, 2024</a>.</p>
<p>Texas-specific data from the Comptroller shows a similar gap: Texas workers with some college or associate degrees earn approximately $8,393 more annually than high school graduates. Source: <a href="https://comptroller.texas.gov/economy/economic-data/colleges/texas.php" target="_blank">Texas Comptroller</a>.</p>

<div class="callout"><strong>The workforce stays local.</strong> 80% of ACC graduates stay in Texas. Community college graduates tend to stay within 50 miles of their college (Emsi/WSJ, 2018). The workforce trained at ACC serves Pflugerville directly.</div>
